text:
tonight: sexual misconduct in stem

when: monday, december 17, 2018, 6-8 pm
where: the university of texas md anderson uthealth graduate school of biomedical sciences, 6767 bertner ave, large classroom, s3.8371, houston, tx 77030

in the midst of the #metoo movement, the ford-kavanaugh hearing, and now department of education secretary betsy devos‚Äô recent proposed changes to the title ix law, we feel it is our duty as an organization that advocates for women in stem to address sexual misconduct in our stem community. 
you are cordially invited to join our open discussion on monday, december 17, where our panelists will inform you about policies on sexual misconduct in the workplace and how to request help inside as well as outside of your institution or workplace, both psychologically and legally. 
rsvp at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/awis-gch-presents-sexual-misconduct-in-stem-tickets-53273703080

networking mixer and reception to follow.

text: i was 23 years old & sexually assaulted by a college classmate. i have no memory of the rape happening. a void in my life. not sure if that was a blessing in disguise or a curse. i can only recall up to a certain point that night before i blacked out. i woke up with bruises all over my body, so much pain, and a whole lot of confusion. the rape examination was on a whole other level that i never thought would be a part of my life. i found out drugs were used. lies were told. maybe i'll share the details of what i remembered leading up to it and afterwards. maybe. the reality hit me later on how easily he could of ended my life that night,leaving my family heartbroken. healing was slow and steady but with god‚Äôs grace, i made it through. i'm now married with kids and i pray none of my children will ever have to face the nightmare of what i went through or any other form of it. i entered counseling to help my healing. one outlet that helped me was writing poetry. to those that have been sexually harassed or assaulted, you are in my prayers. #onenight #brave #daterape #metoo ‚†Ä ‚†Ä

text:
"i really hope that it protects the next generation of young models‚Äô' - #supermodel #bodypositivity #advocate #socialinnovator and #entrepreneur @ashleygraham *
"ashley graham¬†has opened up about how the growth of the¬†#metoo¬†movement has impacted the fashion industry, expressing her wish that it has a positive effect on the careers of up-and-coming models."
*
"in january 2018, the model revealed on american talk show¬†the view¬†how she‚Äôd been sexually harassed during a photo shoot at the age of 17.
she explained how, following the incident, she feared that she‚Äôd never be hired for a modelling job again as she thought that she‚Äôd be regarded as a ‚Äúdifficult model‚Äù.
*
"now at 31 years old, graham describes the changes that she‚Äôs witnessed within the fashion industry since the boom of the #metoo movement; people are actually thinking about their actions and thinking about their words ‚Ä¶ if this #metoo movement had not happened, who‚Äôs to say what would happen to the next generation of girls?
‚Äúi really hope that it protects the next generation of young models.‚Äù
*
"she continues, outlining how coming forward with allegations of sexual abuse would have previously had a detrimental effect on the trajectory of a model‚Äôs career."
*
‚Äúit has given such an incredible voice to women who have felt voiceless, especially as models, because we are the ones who immediately will not get booked for a job,‚Äù *
‚Äúmodels are the ones whose careers can die immediately if you speak up about this kind of stuff.
‚Äúso now your career doesn‚Äôt die, you have a voice and you can use it. and i hope more girls feel empowered by it.‚Äù- in an interview with sabrina barr for #theindependent *

text:
our understanding of gender-based violence is growing. ¬†international day for the elimination of violence against women (25 november) marks the start of 16 days of activism against gender-based violence ‚Äì and thanks to women and non-binary people organising in large numbers, mass movements like #metoo and¬†16 days¬†are gaining traction. 
yet, in many countries and contexts, one group of society is still consistently being excluded from the conversation. worse still, when they try to speak up about their experience of extremely high levels of violence, their testimonies are often undermined or dismissed. ¬†as a result, they face further marginalisation. we‚Äôre talking about #sexworkers. 
with little room to share their experiences in many mainstream women‚Äôs movements, sex workers set up their own commemoration day in 2003 ‚Äì¬†december17 #idevasw

sex workers are often a target of violence because they are perceived to be easy prey. sex workers often can‚Äôt report violence to the police or seek help due to well-founded fears of being arrested, criminalised or evicted. if we are truly serious about ending gender-based violence and supporting survivors, then we need to challenge the #criminalisation and #stigma that drives this violence. and this must start by truly listening to sex workers and understanding their lived experiences.

text:
just in from paris: 
may #19 (2018)
‚Ä¢
this issue of may was conceived around a series of texts by three women writers/artists (elise duryee-browner, cecilia pav√≥n, georgie nettell) who express, through a bio-fictional-essayist form, their current conditions of living, thinking, and working. we worked on the current issue over a period of six months in new york as the debates emerging from the #metoo movement and regarding cultural appropriation became more intense in art communities. instead of addressing directly the moralistic and essentialist dimensions of these binary representations, this issue of may was first imagined as an attempt to initiate a space for writing, to offer some perpectives that could propose another understanding of the new form of ‚Äúcultural war‚Äù we are experiencing now in the western art world. [...]
(more on our website)
‚Ä¢
also edvard munch, sam pulitzer, gianni versace, karl holmqvist, georgia sagri, ruben √∂stlund and much more.
‚Ä¢
available via our website and in the bookshop this week.
‚Ä¢

text:
i know it's a busy time of year. i know we're all working hard to be seen and heard, on behalf of ourselves and others.
.

i've learned a lot in the past couple of months - about the patterns in how sexual violence is perpetrated, about how the human brain responds to trauma, about the multiple systemic and social oppressions working against people of color. this case is, unfortunately, a textbook example of all of that,  and more.
.
.
please. take a moment to call, or email, or tag here/twitter (i sent a dm here on ig, but it doesn't appear to have been read). better yet, do all of the above. .
.
the message is simple: @governorbillhaslam, you didn't create this injustice, but you have it within your power to right at least some of what's wrong. we're counting on you to do the right thing, and grant clemency to cyntoia brown.

text:
this time last year i reached my final rock bottom. i was still in the grips of addiction, i was clean and sober but my eating disorder and self harm caused ruin once again. i was sick and tired of being sick and tired. i had two options keep inflicting this hell till my body gave up or to let go of addiction once and for all after 11 long years. it's been a hell of a fight. but this year i've truly experienced what it means to be alive for the first time, and i've achieved things i never thought possible
.
christmas brightens up the cold dark winter but it is a tricky time for people with mental health illness, addiction, eds, substance abuse, triggers fly left right and centre, fears kick in, and sometimes the festive spirit is darkened. it's okay  to feel distanced from it all, your not alone. take time out for yourself, keep your loved ones close, call a helpline, let someone in. do what you need to do to find some calm in the madness. if you know someone struggling hold out a loving hand, listen and leave the judgements behind. let's all show some kindness and acceptance to ourselves and the ones around us as much as we can manage
.
thank you to my dearest family, boyfriend and friends for supporting me endlessly. for bringing me to life, loving me feircly and igniting hope in me every single day. i am forever grateful üíú
.

text:
today's inspirator is @mattmcgorry. matt mcgorry is an american actor, activist, and feminist. matt even used to be a body builder in the past. he says that he wouldn't do many of the things he did in the past again, but he also says he misses being in that mentality. matt mcgorry is featured on the today show, where he speaks a bit about his acting experience. when he was given his script for the orange is the new black, he discovered he had a scene where he had to be shirtless. this was quite a shocker for him, and put him through a negative state. he started to crash diet which was very unhealthy, but he felt it was needed to become "fit" for the scene. it was like he was pressuring himself to look a certain way because society wanted him to, and he knew that hundreds of people would be watching the show. he says that many actors and actresses go through this all the time. they put this negative image on their body, and think they have to look a certain way to be their role. alongside being on the today show he was even on the manenough episode - "the ugliness of body image" on metoo. matt states that he doesn't think male body image is talked about enough, especially when compared to female body image. men have their insecurities too, but it is understandable that women are put into a lot more pressure. however no body shame is okay in anyway. matt and the other men featured on the show go on to discus that society puts them in a place where they need to have all these qualities to actually identify as a "real man." someone could easily judge them and say, "your not a man because you don't work out or so on so." it's come to this point where they are judged so easily for every little thing they do, and this is what makes them scared to talk about their insercuities. if we can stand up and discus this more often like matt mcgorry, we could make a difference.
-
-
-

text: everyone is still basking in the afterglow of yesterday's win - and so am i. but in truth i can't get over it, not just for our very own catriona, but for the whole pageant as well. watching the broadcast yesterday showed me how much beauty pageants have progressed and evolved from it's name exactly - a contest of beauty representing each country from all over the world into a platform wherein not just physical appearances matter but grace, poise, intellect, compassion, strength and inner beauty. this is the first time that i truly had so many bets to win - not just because of their physical attributes and beauty, but because of the great and interesting background stories and advocacies. breaking all pre-existing prejudice and having the first transgender candidate is definitely something that is proof at how much we, as humans have progressed and evolved. from breaking all the glass ceilings in gender biased professions, to defying archaic cultural beliefs, representing ethnic minorities as well as charging through barriers of social and gender inequality - truly, this pageant was one for the books in our history! this just makes me proud to be alive in this generation of change!üòäüòçüë∏üëèüíÉ #missuniverse #genderequality #translivesmatter #metoo #feminism #heforshe #rawr

triathlon has been a lifeline for so many people and with today's guest, we really got a chance to dive into her experience with finding triathlon in a very dark time of her life. she had decided to press charges against her rapist, but had just found out that prosecutors would not be moving her case forward. even in this era of the #metoo movement, we don't always understand the huge toll it takes on victims to navigate the legal system and try to seek justice. 
so for our guest, suffering the devastation of the incident itself, and the anxiety of navigating this system left her struggling to deal with the aftermath. a chance occurrence of an email arriving from an organization promoting a charity triathlon team brought her an opportunity to find a new way to work through this mental and physical stress. she was hooked immediately, signing up for her second race as soon as she completed the first.
definitely don't miss this interview with @ashleyczac, as she takes us through how triathlon helped her find a new strength and resilience and a way to move forward.

text:
what's your word for 2019? this is the word that was chosen for me. i'll happily accept it! ‚ú®

the word i choose for myself is "authentic". it's not that i wasn't already being authentic. i just haven't been as authentic as i could be. i have been doing a lot of personal development and i know that i choose to put up walls with people to protect myself, i choose to not ask for help because that would make me too vulnerable or needy (baggage from my childhood), and i choose not to speak my mind or share my opinions for fear of being judged or ostracized. ‚ú®

2018 was definitely better for me in terms of owning who i am. i started the following: ‚ú® üë©‚Äçü¶≥i am allowing my hair to grow in gray and stop coloring it. #graypride ‚ú® üë©üèº‚Äçüé§i am owning the fact that i am going through the beginning stages of menopause and embracing it vs fighting it. ‚ú® üîài am speaking up more about social injustices and walking the walk instead of just talking the talk. ‚ú® üó£i am speaking up about my beliefs in circles where i normally would stay quiet because of fears of being ostracized. ‚ú® üîìi am finally opening up the part of me that i had hidden away by sharing my #metoo experience of sexual assault. ‚ú® ü•∞i am learning to be more accepting of myself and my limitations vs trying to "do it all". ‚ú®

2019 is the year i turn 50 and i choose that by the time i turn 50 years old, i am living fully and authentically me in all areas of my life. i feel like i'm finally in a place where i can say i don't give a crap what other people think--i am going to live my life the way i want to live it; i am going to say whatever i want to say (in the most kind way i possibly can, of course); and i'm going to own who i am--fully and completely. ‚ú®

it feels good to be able to say/write that. it only took my 49 years to get to this place üòÇ and i can't wait to see what the next 50 have in store for me! ‚ú®

since losing my three closest friends, i‚Äôve struggled with completely moving on. things like memories, old photos, and the thought of our inside jokes no longer bring a smile to my face. instead, it brings sadness. i think to myself, ‚Äúthese photos and memories are ruined.‚Äù i look at them and all i see is how much things have changed; how it will never go back to normal. my instinct is to delete all of these photos and forget all of these memories, but i can‚Äôt. instead, they weigh on me, reminding me first of the good times, and then of the betrayals. recently, i‚Äôve realized that the best way to move on is to accept that these memories and photos are ruined and these people are not the same anymore. just a few days after posting my previous series on instagram and seeing nothing but positivity, i received a message from one of my former friends‚Äô sister. when i saw the name and the preview of the message pop up on my screen, my hands were shaking and i couldn‚Äôt hold back my tears. her words were sharp and bitter; her goal was to take away from the photos i was so proud of, and tear me down in the process. it worked; i ignored and disregarded every beautiful comment because of one hateful message. i quickly thought, ‚Äúthey‚Äôre even trying to ruin this.‚Äù

text:
three-quarters of women killed by men in the uk in 2017 knew the perpetrator, according to a report on femicide.

the femicide census, conducted by women‚Äôs aid and the campaigner¬†karen ingala smith, found that of the 139 women known to have been killed by men in the uk last year, 105 (76%) knew their killer. thirty women were killed by strangers, with 21 of the 30 killed in terrorist attacks.

the report found that 64 of the women, or 46%, were killed by a current or former intimate partner. another 24 (17%) were killed by a man known to them ‚Äì such as a colleague, neighbour or friend ‚Äì while 17 (12%) were killed by a male family member, of whom 10 were killed¬†by their son. the perpetrator‚Äôs relationship to the victim could not be established in four cases.

read more at femicide in uk: 76% of women killed by men in 2017 knew their killer

https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/18/femicide-in-uk-76-of-women-killed-by-men-in-2017-knew-their-killer

the cbs corporation said its former chief executive, leslie moonves, misled the company about multiple allegations of sexual misconduct and tried to hide evidence as he made a frenzied attempt to save his legacy and reap a lucrative severance. as a result, the company said moonves would not receive his $120 million exit payout.
.
.‚Äúwe have determined that there are grounds to terminate for cause, including his willful and material misfeasance, violation of company policies and breach of his employment contract, as well as his willful failure to cooperate fully with the company‚Äôs investigation,‚Äù the cbs board said in a statement on monday.
.
the board, which met over several days last week, decided on monday afternoon after reviewing information gathered by lawyers hired by the company to investigate claims against moonves, who was forced out in september, as well as the broader workplace culture at the network. moonves ‚Äúengaged in multiple acts of serious nonconsensual sexual misconduct in and outside of the workplace, both before and after he came to cbs in 1995,‚Äù according to a late november draft of the investigators‚Äô report reviewed by the new york times.
.
the lawyers had gathered ample evidence showing moonves had violated cbs policies, including lying to investigators and deleting texts that revealed his attempts to silence an accuser. moonves has denied all the allegations and said any sexual acts he engaged in were consensual.
.
the investigators had spoken with moonves four times and found him to be ‚Äúevasive and untruthful at times and to have deliberately lied about and minimized the extent of his sexual misconduct,‚Äù according to the draft report.
.
moonves could still contest the board‚Äôs ruling and fight for his severance through arbitration. he could argue the company violated the confidentiality terms of his exit agreement when the internal investigation became public.
.
.‚Äúthe conclusions of the cbs board were foreordained and are without merit,‚Äù alexander levander, a lawyer for mr. moonves, said in a statement. #metoo #sexualharassment #moonves

text:
to be a woman is to be told that you are too much, and you are not enough. 
you're wearing too much or not enough. 
saying too much or not enough. 
showing too much emotion but not smiling enough. 
taking up too much space but not eating enough. 
being too muscular and not feminine enough.
being too small and not strong enough. 
from the moment we enter this world we are battling to prove that we are just right. 
battling with ourselves, each other, and most of all, the men who seem to have forgotten where they come from. (psa: it's a woman)
please, the next time you are made to question what excess or deficit inside of you is such an inconvenience, just stop. 
you are whole and the perfect balance of it all, as you stand. 
to be a woman is to be strong, capable, and resilient as hell. 
never too much, and always enough.
.
.
.

text: decembergram day 17: back in october i was recognized as one of the daily journal of commerce‚Äôs women of vision for 2018. it was a huge achievement for me and made all the better by my family flying across the country to be a part of the ceremony! my dad was able to attend while my mom did some heavy lifting watching brooke at home. the #metoo movement has been so inspiring and my decision to be a #constructionlady has meant a lot more effort on my part to be heard and respected in my field of work. i am often on my feminist high horse (which i don‚Äôt apologize for) but let us not forget there are some amazing men along with us. my dad was my champion when i wanted to get my hands dirty instead of playing with dolls, my husband supported and encouraged me transitioning from architecture to construction, and my boss who hired a young women- when it would have been easier to hire a man. #metoo #womeninconstruction #djcoregon #ourchampions @paul.kirchner1 @patharchitecture @carbon12pdx @joanbkirchner @cabotaaage

text:
*dear nation*

dear nation,
it's been six years since you mourned for a girl who lost her life to monsters. you called her every synonym of courage you could find in a thesaurus. you spilled on the streets, screaming for justice. you promised the little girls clenching their tiny hands that it won't happen again. in the same rally, someone groped a girl and you didn't let rage roll down your lips. instead you questioned her character, asking what she was doing so late at night.

dear nation,
a three-year-old gets raped six years later on the same day and you are busy tweeting about celeb marriages. you file firs against comedians because jokes make your blood boil, but crimes against women of this country never do. i wonder what kind of chemistry your body follows!

you buy a smart phone and an internet connection, only to dismiss all the #metoo stories, calling the survivors whores and attention seekers.

you rant about your worries regarding the safety of women but you never question your sons when they mistreat them. you make promises only to break them. you always check whether the rapist is underage and let him go if he is, because children make mistakes and they need to be forgiven. 
but what about those who are punished for the deeds they never committed? i wonder where your sympathy hides when it comes to the survivors, and why it only shows up for the underage rapists.

dear nation,
you will once again spill on the streets, like you did six years ago, seeking justice. but this time too, you won't find it. or will you?

text:
yes. this. i don‚Äôt hear enough about sex in the trauma world, and there can be a lack of trauma-sensitivity in the world of sexual education. that‚Äôs why i created a special 8-week series called reclaim your pleasure. this embodied healing group is for trauma survivors who want to experience more vitality and pleasure in their bodies, but don‚Äôt want to have a ‚Äútantric‚Äù screaming and shaking experience to get there. (anyone else been super triggered in so called sexual healing spaces?) üå∏ what would it be like to explore sensual pleasure while staying regulated and connected to your body? üå∏ how might boundaries and rest be just as pleasurable as stimulation? üå∏ what are some simple & accessible practices that can help you connect to your sensual nature every day? 
you do not have to be perfect, happy or turned on to begin to experience more ease and vitality in your body. you can learn more at kelseygustafson.com üåπ#reclaimyourpleasure #reclaimyourpower #reclaimyourlife

text:
today was a bad mental health day for me. i had a severe panic attack and luckily i had loved ones willing to help. i recognize not everyone is so lucky... on to the book: speak is a book i read in middle school a little too late making this book sadly more relatable. i think it teaches a lot of important subjects. the obvious being rape and sexual assault, but so many aspects come into play especially for the age group of middle school to high school. i think this should be a required read, that it should open up many conversations. i only started this graphic novel but i hope it brings across the same message.

text:
the woman of the week is the incomparable, cristin (@c.fol)
_
cristin is an amazing woman. if you‚Äôre looking for a makeup artist, or even if you already have one, book her (@beauty_fol) ü•∞ she has a laugh that lights up the room and she enjoys enhancing and celebrating the beauty of women of all skin types and tones.
_
this is her story üìö 
_
cristin quit her 9-5 looking for her passion. even though she didn‚Äôt quite know what her passion was at the time, she was clear on a couple of things:
_
1. she had to be creative
2. she didn‚Äôt want to be cooped up in an office
_
with all of her newfound free time, cristin started doing makeup. she spent time doing makeup for her sister and her self. 
_
it was her grandma who reminded her of her worth and told cristin she was way too good to continue offering her skills for free (grandma‚Äôs ftw üíØ) _
she started charging for her services and the rest is history ‚úîÔ∏è
_
@c.fol is a full-time #mua who does makeup for just about any occasion: weddings, photo shoots, baby showers, special events, etc. 
_
my favorite thing about cristin is her ability to connect with others and the awesome playlist she jams too, all while tending to your beauty needs üòò
_
in terms of certification, she currently has her certification in makeup from vizio makeup school and she looks forward to obtaining her esthetician‚Äôs license. her next goal is to focus on brows, lashes and skincare for an affordable price! something that every woman wants! 
_
one of the biggest lessons cristin has learned is that you can make üí∞ doing literally anything as long as you have the passion and the patience to work at it every single day! 
_
@c.fol is a shining example of allowing your passion to come with ease and flow üí´

text: i‚Äôm still trying to process all the feels from this weekend. thank you to everyone that came out to see the eight reindeer monologues. it was very difficult subject matter, but so important to talk about. this piece shows that sexual assault affects everyone differently. some report it right away; others bury it deep and try to move on. it still doesn‚Äôt erase the fact that they were assaulted. it gets even more complicated when you‚Äôre assaulted by a powerful person who does a lot of good for the world. do you ruin the status quo for the entire world when you know that just a small handful of people have been victims of this person? this play was written 20 years ago, but in the last couple of years has become all too relevant and real. the idea of santa raping reindeers is very satirical, but my amazing castmates delivered such strong and truthful performances that we all forgot we were talking about santa. thank you to my 8 reindeers family for bringing this story to life with me. @adam4eyes @shaxmariexoxo @raymac1020 @hollyywouldd @alyssa.nicole91 @adorablydevious @camilleofaragon i‚Äôve learned so much from each and everyone one of you. you are all terrific actors, but more importantly good humans. big thanks to @rycardo1980 for believing in me and casting me in, what you didn‚Äôt know at the time, was my favorite role and 1st choice of the 8. prancer aka ‚Äúhollywood‚Äù was full of personality and a huge diva, but also had a vulnerable side. she was very complex, but relatable as one of the victims who chose not to report. as an actor, this was a really fun and meaty role to play. the last month was an acting master class for me as i dove in and studied this 7-page monologue. ultimately, my hope is that i did this story justice for all the survivors of sexual assault.  i‚Äôm so overjoyed to know that 20% of our proceeds are going to @rainn rainn.org (rape abuse incest national network). thank you again from this mama that doesn‚Äôt get out much. as much as i love my kids, it‚Äôs such an incredible feeling doing something that had nothing to do with being a parent. #morethanamom #actor #actorslife #theeightreindeermonologues #reindeers #santa #metoo #rainn #survivors ‚ù§‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
yael stone speaks to the new york times about her allegations against geoffrey rush: "most women who go public with #metoo stories are fearful for obvious reasons. there is the pain of reliving traumatic experiences. there is the rage of not being believed. and there is sometimes the discomfort of admitting, as ms. stone readily does, that she didn‚Äôt say 'no' and at times even encouraged some of his behavior. she did so, she says, out of fear of offending a mentor and friend.

but ms. stone isn‚Äôt just afraid of the emotional consequences of talking about her allegations against mr. rush, her onetime hero... she is worried that australia‚Äôs defamation laws will drag her into a legal and financial quagmire." read more: https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/16/opinion/metoo-defamation-geoffrey-rush-yael-stone.html

text:
a kentucky radio station is wading into the controversy over the classic christmas song, 'baby, it's cold outside.' while stations across the country are pulling the song from their playlists, waky in elizabethtown is planning a two-hour marathon.
"i'm not sure why it's controversial," said joe fredele, director of programming for waky. "we've played this song for years, you know, this song is older than waky is. it's almost 70 years old.  the song has come under fire as the #metoo movement has brought the issue of consent to the forefront with critics saying the song sends the wrong message.
"we really need to think about the impact that songs have, not just 'baby, it's cold outside,' but numerous songs that we decide to play on the radio," said amy turner, the director of sexual assault services at the center for women and families.
fredele said he supports the #metoo movement but does not understand why this particular song is being singled out.
"this song is not about that. all it is, is a dialogue between a man and a woman, and at the end of the song, you hear them harmonize together, so they're agreeing basically," fredele explained.

a kentucky radio station is wading into the controversy over the classic christmas song, 'baby, it is cold outside.' while stations across the country are pulling the song from their playlists, waky in elizabethtown is planning a two-hour marathon.
"i am not sure why it is controversial," said joe fredele, director of programming for waky. "we've played this song for years, you know, this song is older than waky is. it is almost 70 years old.  the song has come under fire as the  movement has brought the issue of consent to the forefront with critics saying the song sends the wrong message.
"we really need to think about the impact that songs have, not just 'baby, it is cold outside,' but numerous songs that we decide to play on the radio," said amy turner, the director of sexual assault services at the center for women and families.
fredele said he suppos the  movement but does not understand why this paicular song is being singled out.
"this song is not about that. all it is, is a dialogue between a man and a woman, and at the end of the song, you hear them harmonize together, so they're agreeing basically," fredele explained.

text: in addition, treating people so awfully, throughout their most influential years, speaking about the kids in camps, and minorities, the thousands harmed by priests recently, many scenarios; including my life. they're offended. i'm offended. then to society our existance is so out of the standard normal, we meet you, and the moment it's spoken or seen we are to be deemed offensive and put in danger. whether it be race or gender or financial class or experience, none of that is your business. emotions get in the way of logic, as everyone processes trauma in their own time. although it's not traumatic for you, from us to ask for help and speak those words depending on the issue, and the reason we don't is due to, either being threatened from the person or previously asking and having it go so wrong or both. certain people can't bear to know or understand or acknowledge the violence and hate crimes. understanding theres a different priority in life for you other than safety, its not your experience, its not your life. its hard for me to communicate, because of the badgering and threats. the justice system that hasn't been working at righteous standard for all, and needs to be reestablished. to be considered a threat for existing and surviving issues so many people face and are silenced for experiencing, further continuing violence. for what, society to remain ignorant; that does no good. either way, finally speaking out kinda feels like i just broke the sound barrier, with the speed of light a little bit. with help.  mouse raptor goes roar. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #roar #thetyrantfearsthepoet #outherewherethedangerbee #nojusticenopeace

text:
#roma adalah seiris kehidupan yang disajikan secara empatik lewat presisi kamera arri alexa 65, dengan kontrol penuh dari alfonso cuar√≥n sebagai sutradara dan penata kamera. lahir, tumbuh dan berkembang di mexico city, salah satu dari three amigos ini memberikan penuturan yang personal dan sentimental tentang perjuangan seorang prt untuk melawan kerasnya hidup di tengah kekacauan politik mexico di akhir 1970an.

lewat tangan ambisiusnya, kisah yang bersumber dari pengalaman seorang pengasuh anak yang merawatnya di masa kecil ini menjadi sebuah pengalaman sinematik yang transendental. sinematografi yang spektakuler dan perfeksionis serta debut akting yalitza aparicio sebagai cleo mampu menjamah setiap lapisan emosional yang dapat membuat kita merasakan pengalaman bercerita yang selalu berbeda, tidak peduli berapa kali pun kita menonton ulang. terlebih, seperti film film alfonso cuar√≥n sebelumnya, roma menceritakan kemalangan seseorang yang terjebak di dalam situasi lingkungan yang tidak pernah ia duga dengan memberikan porsi lebih pada aspek lingkungan untuk menggerakkan plot dan mengembangkan karakter para tokohnya.

masih mengkampanyekan #metoo, film ini juga mengajak para perempuan untuk saling menjaga dan mendukung satu sama lain, terutama dari pria-pria seperti ferm√≠n dan sr. antonio yang pengecut serta tidak becus dalam mengurusi persoalan sepele.

sudah menonton film ini? yuk diskusi bersama kami!

text:
i don't like the term 'toxic masculinity'. it's unfair and unhelpful.
.. i think it is wrong that maleness is portrayed as something negative and dangerous. it's not fair on men (and boys) and it is not going to help solve the problem of the violence and abuse perpetrated by a minority.
.. it's also counterproductive. the backlash to feminism and the #metoo movement likes to label outspoken women as men haters and feminazis (another term i do not like!) . when female commentators and journalists use generalisations like 'toxic masculinity' they feed into the false narrative that men are under threat. yes the privileged position held by some men (in western europe that is white, straight and wealthy ones) is being challenged but this is only seen as a threat by those who don't want equality. .. what do you think? we won't fall out if you don't agree.. but do be kind!

text:
waiting.
in a regional court to testify as a dr witness to a rape case of a minor 18 months ago.
the versatility of medicine is broad. it has certainly led me to many journeys and adventures of bridging physical mental and heart health.
i'm never gonna be the hero at the trauma resus.
im not gonna be that work through the night and day for weeks and sabotage my family. done that.
my pledge to world peace is my humble piecemeal.
gentle birth brings peace on earth.
it's about connection. it's about truth.
and walking the two.
today is a different #metoo
i'm here for all woman and girls.
this young woman is rising.
i hope my testimony helps towards this material justice.
spiritually. the universe has our back. always.
#betrue

text:
listen to what @folustorms @jennygentet the boss , and @toyinabraham  had to say on the inclusion of women in politics.

so last week, nigerians watched the #vpdebates and 5 political parties were represented by their candidates. 2 female vice presidential aspirants and 3 male vice presidential aspirants. 
from the various aspirants, it was easy to point out the ones who came with wits, facts, figures, intellect, blame game and the ones who came without researching, who had the ideas but were not articulate (give me another synonym). i really am very intentional about my questions at any interview, as much as we want women involved, we should be ready and not let anyone out smart us!  women should not allow themselves to be choosen as running mates, because it plays to the emotions of people, then only for them to be relegated in the end. let's not be used to sell a fake dream because of the #metoo era. let's rule because we know our history, we know antecedents, we can profere solutions, we have knowledge, we have influence and yes it is mother earth so we rule the earth because we earned it! 
#mediagirl #prgirl #media #entertainment #lifestyle #style #fashion #event #redcarpet #blackcarpet #politics #journalism

text:
we have a new  group on fb called speak out sisterhood (s.o.s)

for all those who have faced sexual violence and want to be able to seek support, friendship, love and have ears listen.

this group is for you. 
if you are just coming to terms with your experiences or are further on in your journey you are welcome to join. we are not counsellors, but have experiences that maybe akin to yours. 
we will never say, we know how you feel because we dont, but we are here to listen and love. 
for those of you who worry about speaking out and being believed you will be amongst other's who understand and stand with you, sisters  in arms.

we believe. 
https://www.facebook.com/groups/805644186440105/

text:
i think it‚Äôs time for me to address this harvey weinstein scandal. 
i just want to start off, if you have any other information, please feel free to dm me. second of all, i obviously don‚Äôt know the whole truth, and most of you don‚Äôt either. please don‚Äôt attack me because of my opinions. you don‚Äôt know the full story. 
i will always be on jennifer‚Äôs side, no matter what happens. i was unsure of harvey, even when he and jennifer were friends. there were so many allegations against him that i was always suspicious. but after this has happened i don‚Äôt think i can ever forgive him for all this shit that he has put jennifer through. 
here are the facts: in 2013, harvey weinstein lured a new, small actress into having sex with him, by saying they were meeting to discuss her career. he used jennifer‚Äôs name to seduce her, his words being ‚Äúi slept with jennifer lawrence and look where she is, she has just won an oscar." he apparently told the jane doe actress. he then went on to sleep with her, on the pretense that he had slept with jennifer and that he had made her who she was, the talented, successful actress. this is completely wrong. before she met harvey she had already been nominated for one oscar, one golden globe and starred in two massive franchises, xmen and hunger games. she did not need weinstein to make her more successful. she was already extremely successfully before she even worked with him. i completely believe her when she says that she never slept with him, jennifer and harvey‚Äôs relationship was purely professional. so everyone stop believing the man who already has many sexual assault claims against him and start believing the talented women who are being victimized and blamed for something that someone did to them, something that they couldn‚Äôt help. it‚Äôs not their fault. and it‚Äôs certainly not jennifer‚Äôs fault. so stop blaming her.

text:
the survivor learns to always be vigilant, because there could be unexpected cruelty at any moment or any time. hypervigilance, which is a symptom of ptsd, keeps victims in a constant state of stress. 
it‚Äôs normal for survivors of sexual violence to experience feelings of anxiety, stress, or fear. if these feelings become severe, last more than a few weeks, or interrupt your day-to-day life, it might be a condition known as post-traumatic stress disorder (ptsd). post-traumatic stress disorder is an anxiety disorder that can result from a traumatic event.¬† survivors might experience uncharacteristic feelings of stress, fear, anxiety, and nervousness‚Äîand this is perfectly normal. with ptsd, these feelings are extreme, can cause you to feel constantly in danger, and make it difficult to function in everyday life.

ptsd nightmares aren't always exact replays of the event. sometimes they replay the emotions the victim felt during the event, like fear, helplessness, and sadness.

symptoms of ptsd fall under 4 categories:

1) relieving the event (e.g, flashbacks, nightmares).
2) hypervigilance (e.g, sleeping difficulties, paranoia).
3) feeling emotionally numb (e.g, loss of interest in activities the victim previously enjoyed).
4) avoiding reminders of the event (e.g, avoidance of things that are reminders of the event). our infographic shows some data on ptsd and the symptoms.

text:
short story: i‚Äôm no artist, but have been feeling artsy lately

long story: i‚Äôve been extremely inspired by women as a whole over 2018. i‚Äôve seen two of my best friends experience motherhood. another friend is not only a mother, but managed to work, go to school, and published two novels this past year. some women in my life have graduated and continued on to their dream careers, others have traveled to new places to follow their dreams of no careers.  i‚Äôve seen a couple of the strongest women i know deal with domestic violence and it‚Äôs consequences. and i‚Äôve seen the togetherness women throughout the world have gained through the protests and #metoo movements, knowing that their voice is heard if not only by the many, many women who have been through similar situations. i have so many women that i look up to every freakin‚Äô day that help remind me of the woman i hope to be. i thank all of you wonderful goddesses for being who you are. you are strong, you are intelligent, you are beautiful, you are women. this is history. our time is now.

text:
leri la delegazione della commissione  femm del parlamento europeo ha visitato la nostra casa, abbiamo raccontato cosa facciamo tutti i giorni per costruire spazi per le donne e per tutte le persone consapevoli che combattere la violenza significa aprire i territori alla forza e all'organizzazione spontanea delle donne. lucha √® solo una tappa di una visita ufficiale per dimostrare supporto a tutte le associazioni femministe che erano con noi nell'audizione di settembre presso il parlament europeo e che combattono una guerra assurda contro i tagli ai fondi, le minacce di chiusura e le denigrazioni politiche e culturali come il centro donne dalia centrodonna l.i.s.a. assolei onlus sportello donna  casa della donna di pisa casa delle donne viareggio pronto donna e casa internazionale delle donne
ad un anno dal lancio della campagna #luchaysiestanonsivende l'esperienza di lucha y siesta deve ancora difendersi da possibili vendite dello stabile, come ci diceva ieri la eurodeputata monika vana in altri paesi il settore pubblico riconosce il valore di nuove sperimentazioni sociali prima che quello economico patrimoniale, ci diceva che a vienna, dove vivono meno di 2 miliorni di persone, esistono 5 case per donne che escono dalla violenza con circa 40 posti l'una e che il settore delle case popolari fornisce sempre una risposta valida. insieme a eleonora forenza abbiamo ragionato su come andare avanti nella difesa degli spazi delle donne e ringraziamo monica lozzi presidente vii municipio di roma - m5s per aver accettato il nostro invito e quelle che non hanno potuto partecipare per altri impegni. domani la delegazione sar√† presso la casa internazionale delle donne . le donne unite cambiano il mondo!
.
.
.

text: efectivamente, esto no es una guerra de las mujeres contra los hombres, pues los amamos, respetamos y admiramos (para los que no sepan que significa feminismo busquen su definici√≥n); esto es una guerra de las mujeres por la injusticia, por la falta de igualdad real, por la falta de empat√≠a y por la indiferencia hacia todo aquello que nos ha discriminado desde siempre. esto es una guerra por el cambio social, no es personal!.por eso quiero decir gracias a todos los hombres que al menos se han parado a pensar en lo que las mujeres queremos decir, en escuchar nuestras horribles experiencias por el simple hecho de no tener pene!!! y gracias de verdad por no empujarnos sino acompa√±arnos como iguales por un cambio real, para que nuestras futuras hijas sean libres. #niunamas #feminismo #feminist #yositecreo #metoo #todassomosdianaquer #todassomoslaura

text:
my quilt ‚Äúwhy i‚Äôm a feminist‚Äù was accepted to quiltcon. the idea for this piece came to me a couple years ago, and as much as i tried to be too busy to make it, it insisted on being created. .
it‚Äôs a personal story of the death by a thousand cuts that the patriarchy has brought to bear on me as a  girl, as a woman. . 
as much as i‚Äôm proud of #metoo as a movement, its shorthand can hide the horrors of abuses. you read ‚Äúme too‚Äù and you know the details aren‚Äôt good, but you can avoid them when they‚Äôre buried under a hashtag. .
this story is the details. it‚Äôs not an easy read. and lemme tell you, stitching my way through it was both cathartic and harrowing. but i know so many women who can tell an equally harrowing tale of similar treatment in their lives. and that is really the story. .
i‚Äôve decided that i‚Äôll wait until it hangs at qc to share the whole picture. i‚Äôm recovering from medical stuff, and i‚Äôm super tender both physically and emotionally. i‚Äôm absolutely willing to be engaged with the conversations i know this piece will create, but not while i‚Äôm still healing. so much of being raised female is about being expected to take care of everyone to the detriment of taking care of yourself. today, i‚Äôm going against the grain of that upbringing and working my self care first üòò
üß°
#samhunterfineart #quiltcon2019 #metoo #ihavesomethingtosay #wordgirlforever #embroidery #huntersdesignstudio

.

text_retweet:
white and rich in america... #metoo 
#repost @tattle_tailzz
„Éª„Éª„Éª
a woman who says she was just 16 when she became woody allen's mistress in the 1970s is speaking out. babi christina engelhardt, who says she was a teen model when she met the famed director in 1976, opened up to the hollywood reporter about her alleged eight-year affair with the "annie hall" filmmaker. 
engelhardt, who now goes by christina engelhardt, told thr that she met allen at the restaurant and celebrity hotspot elaine's and  gave him her phone number. she said soon, allen, who was 41 at the time, called her and invited her to his fifth avenue penthouse apartment. 
engelhardt said allen never asked her how old she was, but she told him she was still in high school. 
engelhardt told thr that she and allen became physically intimate at his apartment within weeks, months before she turned 17, which is the legal age of consent in new york. 
the former model, now 59, said she has been thinking about it recently in light of the #metoo movement and controversy surrounding allen, whose adopted daughter dylan farrow has accused him of sexual abuse. engelhardt made it clear that she is "not attacking woody" and said she simply wants to provide perspective. "this is not 'bring down this man,'" she said in the interview. "i'm talking about my love story. this made me who i am. i have no regrets." she said that she was responsible for staying in the relationship. allen declined to comment for the story. engelhardt, now a mother of two, said that she was disappointed when allen introduced her to his "girlfriend," mia farrow, since she thought she was allen's girlfriend. but engelhardt said that she later participated in threesomes with farrow and allen. 
farrow declined to comment. 
she said that she knows actress stacey nelkin, who dated allen when she was 17, also says she was allen's "manhattan" muse, though engelhardt said, "i was like, 'whatever.'" she said she met two of allen's other young girlfriends during threesomes. but she appears to look fondly on the film, saying it reminds her "why i thought he was so interesting ‚Äî his wit is magnetic." read more at thr or cbs #metoo

text:
a recent study¬†examined female chess players to see if it were possible¬†to identify proof of stereotype threat. first, the researchers¬†surveyed 77 women to see whether they knew that many think men are better at chess than women.¬†(you can‚Äôt be threatened by a stereotype you don‚Äôt know exists.)¬†since they‚Äôre chess players, they certainly did. there is only one woman in the top 100 chess players in the world.

next, the researchers watched men and women play chess at twelve different tournaments. they saw¬†219 girls between the ages of 5 and 15 play. when they compared how the girls should have done,¬†based on their rankings and previous play,¬†and how they actually did, voil√†:¬†‚Äúfemales performed worse than expected when playing against a male opponent, achieving 83% of the expected success based on their own and their opponent‚Äôs prerating," they write.

not only did the study find that stereotype had an impact on games in the real world, they also found it had an impact on players in the long run:¬†‚Äúthose most vulnerable to stereotype threat were less likely to continue playing in future chess tournaments.‚Äù #stereotypethreat #biases #sexism #stereotypes #prejudice #pride #psychologicalfacts

text:
use your voice. speak. share your truth, your heart, from your core. it doesn't need to be pretty, eloquent, or clothed in all the right words. don't wait until you can dress it up and make it presentable or palatable to the listener. just get it out. get it out of you. now. as is. rescue yourself; get to safety. whatever it takes to set those words free, in their most raw, most honest, naked selves - do it - otherwise they, and you, stay trapped. in pain, in fear, in danger. your mouth and your pen, they're your fire escape. go.
.
for those still afraid, or pausing to consider self-destruction instead, remember: 'you own everything that happened to you. tell your stories. if people wanted you to write warmly about them, they should have behaved better.'
.
üíúüî•üíõ
.
.
.
.
.

text:
imagine your tutor at university touching you inappropriately and then your well known colleague suggesting you become a grocer. the two men that were supposed to respect you end up betraying you. i have surprisingly experienced a fair  deal of sexual harassment and therefore, i understand what it is like to be in such a uncomfortable and confused state of mind. some males are intimidated by a women‚Äôs success or intelligence. quite profoundly, we are mistakenly thought that males have their right to play rough or have a ego centred view of life. i think this is where the problem starts. at a women in medicine event i was speaking at, they were only two men that attended. it is in my sincere beliefs that males demonstrate more interest in issues surrounding gender equality. moreover, we need to put in systems of reporting sexual harassment in public environments where women‚Äôs experiences of harassment and violence are considered and rightfully and fairly dealt with. women are rarely taught how to deal with such situations that we can keep it secretive especially in a work setting in the fear of being made redundant or losing marks. and those males are usually highly influential men, very popular and respected. that it can be hard for others to picture them saying or doing it. and thus, we quietly fear that no one will take us seriously. however. we, women, need to stop being scared and start speaking up because if we do not speak up, people will not hear us.  be courageous. call it out, as you see or hear it. it will better the tomorrow for the next generation of women. we are powerful forces in the universe and united, hand in hand, we can make a difference in this area. no women deserves to feel threatened or uncomfortable just because she‚Äôs a women. and all men, engaging in sexual harassment need to face serious consequences. so be brave today and say no to sexual harassment. i hope our continued ranting will do us justice and make our voices heard. 
#feminism #feminist #sexualharassment #genderequality #womensrights #metoo #inspirational #selfhelp #womenempowerment

text:
you connect most with clients who are a mirror of who you used to be, or the parts of you that you are continuing to work on.  for me, this means i connect deepest with those who have struggled their entire life with excess weight.  it may not be 100+ lbs, but it's most definitely a pattern of yo-yo dieting they have not been able to break through.
.
.
it's officially been 8 years since my efforts to break this cycle began.  it first began as an obligation to get my health in check to obtain the career i spent 4 years in school for.  i never imagined my journey would become what it is today.  breaking lifelong cycles of overeating, emotional dependency on food, and habitual hiding indulgences, has allowed me to share hope with others.
.
.
i'd love to tell you there's an easy fix, or a magic pill. but....we both know you've already tried those magic pills and it didn't work, did it?  what does work is getting quiet.  silence the noise around you about the next big fad, the next "magic diet" and the next contraption that guarantees 20lbs lost or your money back. .
.
get quiet, so you can get honest today.  you have been unable to shed the pounds because you're scared of how it will feel.  you're scared of what people will think, and if their love for you will change.  you're afraid of the work it's going to take in the gym or in the kitchen and you're afraid of being uncomfortable.  you know what life is like at 265lbs, 300lbs, 150, etc.  but do you know what life will feel like at your goal weight?  no. .
.
what would it mean for you to go out in public and not fear running into anyone you know?  what would it mean for you to go out to eat and not have instant anxiety over the menu because you'll feel "guilty" if you don't eat "healthy" tonight?  what would it feel like to actually come to a deeper understanding of who you are in this world?
.
.
it took me a lot of "do-overs" to finally understand (and accept) that until i worked on learning how to love myself more, i was never going to win this battle.  that is the magic.  that is what breaks the cycle.

text:
"you cannot hide yourself and expect to be seen." ever see something that leaves you feeling exposed? something that shakes you to your core? that was me when this quote from @minaa_b came across my feed in a @blackgirlinom post. her story literally stopped me in my tracks with empathy.

she was me. 
and this was my 2018. ...this is where posting this gets hard. this is the part where i bring the darkest parts of my being to light. i don't usually do this, but have been feeling called to. and if anything i write or say can make someone else feel seen, like mina's post did for me, it's worth the discomfort... 2018. ten months ago i was raped on a date at the ace hotel. 
within seconds, my body was no longer mine. my body wasn't something i owned. wasn't something i controlled. it was his to be used. 
seconds. 
seconds i can't have back or erase no matter how much i tried.

and in 2018 erasing those seconds proved to be impossible. 2018 was the year cosby was sentenced, dr. ford testified, and millions of women continued to say #metoo. 
2018 was the year where i looked at you and smiled, but i wasn't there. it was the year i hid my pain in plain sight. it was the year where i blamed myself, lost trust, was late, flaked, where i buried myself in my work, stopped taking care of my body, and waited for my body to be taken for a 4th time.

it was the year where i hid myself and expected to be seen.

then i got sick. and it felt like my body gave me an ultimatum: consume this pain or purge it.

so i'm purging. now, 2018 was the year where i said f**k that guy, f**k those guys. you took seconds, but you can't have forever.

i'm ending 2018 consumed in gratitude.

2018 was the year where i had the most incredible friends and family in the world. 
i'm ending 2018 celebrating my birthday with all the humans who made me feel safe. this past weekend i invited my friends to get gussied up for a beautiful dinner and then head to the ace to reclaim a space that took so much. 
sexual assult doesn't define us, it defines them. 
thank you for being there for me. cheers to only the best people, puppies, and pizza in 2019!

and this was my 2018. ...this is where posting this gets hard. this is the pa where i bring the darkest pas of my being to light. i do not usually do this, but have been feeling called to. and if anything i write or say can make someone else feel seen, like mina's post did for me, it is woh the discomfo... 2018. ten months ago i was raped on a date at the ace hotel. 
within seconds, my body was no longer mine. my body wasn't something i owned. wasn't something i controlled. it was his to be used. 
seconds. 
seconds i can not have back or erase no matter how much i tried.

and in 2018 erasing those seconds proved to be impossible. 2018 was the year cosby was sentenced, dr. ford testified, and millions of women continued to say  
2018 was the year where i looked at you and smiled, but i wasn't there. it was the year i hid my pain in plain sight. it was the year where i blamed myself, lost trust, was late, flaked, where i buried myself in my work, stopped taking care of my body, and waited for my body to be taken for a 4th time.

it was the year where i hid myself and expected to be seen.

then i got sick. and it felt like my body gave me an ultimatum: consume this pain or purge it.

so i am purging. now, 2018 was the year where i said f**k that guy, f**k those guys. you took seconds, but you can not have forever.

i am ending 2018 consumed in gratitude.

2018 was the year where i had the most incredible friends and family in the world. 
i am ending 2018 celebrating my bihday with all the humans who made me feel safe. this past weekend i invited my friends to get gussied up for a beautiful dinner and then head to the ace to reclaim a space that took so much. 
sexual assult does not define us, it defines them. 
thank you for being there for me. cheers to only the best people, puppies, and pizza in 2019!

text:
12 announcements have been launched by the uk government today to tackle sexual harassment at work.

the government will: 
run awareness raising work with advisory conciliation and arbitration service (acas), equality and human rights committee (ehrc) and employers
commission a survey to gather regular data on the prevalence of sexual harassment
consult on non-disclosure agreements
consult on the evidence base for a new legal duty on employers to prevent sexual harassment in the workplace
consult on strengthening and clarifying the laws on third party harassment in the workplace
consult on whether further legal protections are required for interns and volunteers
consult to explore the evidence for extending employment tribunal time limits for equality act 2010 cases
ensure the public sector takes action to tackle and prevent sexual harassment
work with regulators for whom sexual harassment is particularly relevant to ensure they are taking appropriate action
consider whether further learnings can be taken from the criminal justice system to use in the employment tribunal system, to ensure vulnerable claimants have appropriate protection
check that the list of organisations who can receive ‚Äòwhistleblowing‚Äô information includes the right bodies

it‚Äôs such a shame there is nothing practical in here. it sounds like a lot of talk and little action to me. what do you think?  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

contact governor haslam at (615) 741-2001 -  black lives matter nashville, as well as activists nationwide, are calling on us to put pressure on tennessee‚Äôs outgoing governor to grant clemency to sex trafficking victim, cyntoia brown.

cyntoia brown was being abused emotionally and physically by a pimp who often held her at gunpoint.

in 2004 16 year old cyntoia brown was forced to have sex with a 43 year old man and fearing for her life she shot him with one of his many guns. for this, cyntoia brown was given life in prison for first-degree murder.

according to the root, "she was granted a clemency hearing earlier this year but her petition was eventually denied by the tennessee board of probation and parole. although the u.s. supreme court has ruled that life sentences without the possibility of parole for juveniles are unconstitutional, the tennessee supreme court later said that brown would have to serve at least 51 years of her sentence before she is granted parole." we must pressure tennessee governor bill haslam to grant her clemency before he leaves office in january!

black lives matter nashville wrote in a statement, "a system that disproportionately and intimately harms people of color, women, and other marginalized peoples is a matter of human rights. a system that allows the state of tennessee to have a unique sentencing of 51 years is a matter of human rights.‚Äù contact governor haslam at (615) 741-2001 to demand #clemency4cyntoiabrown.

üíîrp @dxepriya when i reached inside of this baby calf's hutch, what i saw broke me. she was covered in diarrhea, which for calves can be extremely deadly. her filthy hutch had no bedding, no water, and no food. the only thing she could call her own is the ear-tag that was forcibly pierced into her ear when she was just a few days old. but the most haunting part of this experience was how lonely she was.
her loneliness is a routine practice in the dairy industry which depends on separating mothers from their babies. when julianne, alicia and i found angel at raymar ranch, she too was separated from her mom. but not only that, angel was thrown away like trash in a graveyard, waiting to die.

when i tried to help angel, she was ripped away from my arms. why is it that the industry sees us helping animals, their response is to punish us? it's because the truth is so scary that they feel it's criminal to publicize it.

if animal rights activists are considered criminals for trying to save baby cows from a life of misery and loneliness, we need more, not less of us. #dairyfree #dairy #govegan #crueltyfree #meat #hamburger #burger #pizzahut #pizzapizza #ilovepizza #cheesecake #cheesecakefactory #cheesey #cheeseboard #creamy #cream #creamcheese #dairyisscary #stopseparatingfamilies #burgerking #tacobell #burrito #quesadilla #vegano #metoo #seperation #donttakeourplanetforgranted (via #easyrepost @appkottage)

text_retweet:
i came across this post a few days ago and it immediately struck a cord. we suffer as young doctors, not because of increased demands of our jobs and training, but also at the hand of higher professionals that lack the basics of teaching and nourishing the future generations in medical practice. i have personally suffered at the hands of trainers who projected their own insecurities and lack of professionalism and perhaps prior unfortunate pain inflicted by their own trainers with some embarking on personal vendettas. 
there has to be a means to assess trainers based on their competency of how they teach and deliver knowledge with respect and dignity and not what they teach. trainers have to be able to separate their lives and prior psychological experiences from their teaching rather than contributing to a sad trajectory, or simply they should not be allowed to teach irrespective of the value of their knowledge or medical experience. 
hang in there everyone. not because it will get better, but because we will rise up in a movement! #metoo

#repost from @humansofny ‚Äúi just finished medical school.  now i‚Äôm heading to residency, which is supposed to be even tougher.  i‚Äôve been working sixteen-hour days.  then i‚Äôm expected to study every night when i get home.  some of my classmates only sleep three hours per night.  i tried that for a few months during my surgery rotation, but i ended up getting really depressed.  i felt completely depersonalized.  everything seemed like a dream.  to make matters worse, a lot of the instructors are jerks.  i think they went through hell when they were students, so they feel like they should put us through hell.  on the first day of rotations, my attending physician told me: ‚Äòi‚Äôm an asshole, but i‚Äôll make you a better doctor.‚Äô he made fun of me in front of other students.  he put me down in front of patients.  he‚Äôd threaten to kick me out every day.  i guess they‚Äôre trying to weed people out and make strong doctors.  but they‚Äôre just traumatizing people.  they‚Äôre making us apathetic.  i got into medicine because i really wanted to make a difference in people‚Äôs lives.  but after going through hell, i just don‚Äôt care anymore.‚Äù

text:
the biggest fashion moments of #2018
_ 
1. #metoo: at the golden globes, attendees planned a fashion blackout, using this as a platform to speak out about sexual harassment while standing in solidarity with survivors. 
_
2. #phenomenallylatina: latinas in hollywood got united to speak up about #latinaequalpayday and to encourage people to #vote. 
_
3. puerto rican designer @stellanolasco used the #nyfw spotlight to speak up about the situation of puerto rico after hurricane maria
_
4. #furfree zone: brands like chanel, burberry, dkny, michael kors, versace, and coach have all declared they'd be going fur-free. 
_
5. #curvy all the way: fashion designers speak up about the inclusivity in the fashion industry.

text_retweet:
repost by @syaiesh:  i came across this post a few days ago and it immediately struck a cord. we suffer as young doctors, not because of increased demands of our jobs and training, but also at the hand of higher professionals that lack the basics of teaching and nourishing the future generations in medical practice. i have personally suffered at the hands of trainers who projected their own insecurities and lack of professionalism and perhaps prior unfortunate pain inflicted by their own trainers with some embarking on personal vendettas. 
there has to be a means to assess trainers based on their competency of how they teach and deliver knowledge with respect and dignity and not what they teach. trainers have to be able to separate their lives and prior psychological experiences from their teaching rather than contributing to a sad trajectory, or simply they should not be allowed to teach irrespective of the value of their knowledge or medical experience. 
hang in there everyone. not because it will get better, but because we will rise up in a movement! #metoo

text:
suicide is the biggest killer of men under 35. 
men report significantly lower life satisfaction than women. men make up 76% of all suicides. men make up 
95% of the prison population. men make up 73% of all adults who go missing and men make up 87% of rough sleepers.
.
.
.

@lprh_ delves into masculinity in 2018, what's toxicity, and how does it impact the lives of men, and the lives of all.
.
.

link in bio, thanks to the incredibly talented @gabriellamussurakis for her beautiful artwork on this piece.

#mentalhealth #toxicmasculinity #metoo #masculinity #gender #race #identity

text:
i saw a comedy sketch on show with a female detective and a female counsellor talking to a man who's just been robbed at knife point. it was such a clever way of making others think about rape culture and how victims of sexual violence are treated by authorities. ‚ûñ

it was also a reminder of how, to this day, a victim is made to bare some responsibility in what they didn't have any responsibility in doing. can we get this to change?  can we not have rape be one of the most underreported crimes due to this kind of treatment?
